The paper deals with combinatorial optimization problems, which are typically studied in the computer science subfield of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The use of stochastic information and the need to pay a price for obtaining more information suggests a connection to game theory (cs.GT) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The mention of facility location and prize-collecting Steiner tree problems suggests a connection to operations research (cs.RO). Finally, the use of approximation algorithms suggests a connection to computational complexity theory (cs.CC).
